article.description: Takia Starks scored 21 points to lead Texas A&M (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today, No. 4 AP) to a 64-50 victory over TCU (No. 25 ESPN/USA Today, No. 24 AP) on Sunday afternoon.
article.shortLinkText: No. 3 Texas A&M topples No. 25 TCU
article.headline: Starks leads Texas A&M as TCU loses second straight
article.linkText: Starks, No. 3 Texas A&M roll over No. 25 TCU
article.story:
COLLEGE STATION, Texas -- Takia Starks' ability to move without the ball caused TCU big problems in Texas A&M's 64-50 victory over the Lady Frogs (No. 25 ESPN/USA Today, No. 24 AP) on Sunday afternoon.

"It's like a chicken running with its head cut off," said Starks, who led the Aggies (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today, No. 4 AP) with 21 points. "With the quick release I have, I try to use that to my advantage."

Texas A&M forward La Toya Micheaux tied a career high with 14 rebounds and added four steals, both game highs before a season-high crowd of 5,395.

Starks, in constant motion on offense, finished 8-for-14 from the floor, including 2 of 4 from the 3-point line.

"We're just trying to [drop] the hammer on anybody we play," Micheaux said of defeating a ranked opponent. "This year we decided as seniors to go all out in all of our games."

The Aggies (10-0) are off to a school record start, and on Sunday they whipped the Lady Frogs (8-4) with a high-octane defensive outing.

TCU committed a season-high 23 turnovers, as the Aggies had 16 steals.

"We didn't handle their pressure very well," TCU coach Jeff Mittie said. "It's the best pressure we've seen this year."

The Aggies only made 2 of 15 3-pointers, but countered their poor perimeter shooting by holding TCU to 16 of 49 (32.7 percent) from the floor.

The Lady Frogs attempted only 18 shots at halftime -- 21 fewer than the Aggies to that point, who led 35-21 at the break.

"They're always on you defensively," said TCU guard TK LaFleur, who scored a game-high 22 points. "It's hard to even catch the ball. That made it tough to get our offense going."

Texas A&M's strong showing against a ranked opponent also had Micheaux hoping for big things the rest of the way for the Aggies, who don't play again until Dec. 30, when they host New Mexico.

"We want to try and go undefeated if we can," Micheaux said. "And take it as far as we can. This is probably the best team I've played on. Matter of fact, it is. We have the talent to take it to that level."

Texas A&M coach Gary Blair dismissed Micheaux's bravado as his forward simply feeling good following a big victory. One before a host of high-school recruits, including touted Houston-area senior forward Kelsey Bone.

"I want to win every ball game, but we're not making any predictions," Blair said. "Remember, we were picked fifth in our conference."
